Q19: During the deceleration phase, our main question was: given the current levels of herd immunity, if the restriction x were to be lifted on day y, when do we expect to see the next wave and how big can it be? would it overwhelm hospitals?
Q21: During the early phase of 2020, before the emergence of variants with increased transmissibility and immune escape properties, we were only communicating epidemic forecasts in relation to lifting/implementing pharmaceutical (vaccines) and non-pharmaceutical interventions. Particularly after the emergence of Delta in Iran, there was a growing concern over the impact of novel variants on the severity of future waves in which case, it was much harder to make statements with good confidence about what may happen next. The uncertainties were compounded by lack of information on true disease prevalence and number of vaccinated individuals. This would significantly restrict us in trusting the reliability of epidemic forecast models.
Q23: The major limitation was scarcity of serological, epidemiological, and genomic data of the virus both at the province and national levels. This would substantially restrict any discussion around the true prevalence and burden of the disease across the country

Q21:
Range of Possible Outcomes: When presenting forecasts, make sure to provide a range of possible outcomes (e.g., best-case, worst-case, and most likely scenarios). This helps stakeholders understand that epidemic forecasts offer probabilities rather than certainties.
Confidence Intervals: If available, use confidence intervals to show the statistical range of uncertainty. For example, "Given the current transmission rates, we estimate the number of cases could reach between 1,000 and 3,000 within the next two weeks, with a 90% confidence level."
Q23:
Inconsistent or Incomplete Data: Explain that epidemic forecasts rely on accurate, up-to-date data. Early in the pandemic, data collection and reporting may have been inconsistent or incomplete. Some regions may have had limited testing or underreported cases, making it challenging to create accurate models.
Changes in Data Reporting: Point out that changes in testing protocols, case definitions, or reporting practices during the pandemic (e.g., delays in reporting or changes in case categorization) could lead to discrepancies in the data, potentially affecting the forecasts.

Q19:
Please note that in the above, there was not much discussion of herd immunity - everyone understood the concept well, and we discussed it briefly, but the intent was to prevent infection - ideally until vaccination was available.
When I ticked the box about herd immunity and school opening, I am referring specifically to school opening (apart from a brief discussion in the acceleration phase).
We presented information on ventilators early on - the taskforce did not specifically ask for it - but in this setting it was simply not a useful piece of data (lack of ventilators).
Q21:
All taskforce members were experienced epidemilogists. At each presentation I went through all the data underlying the modelling to show the uncertainty in parameters, and gave credible intervals with outputs. 
As an experienced modeller with a multidisciplinary background I also discussed what my 'best guess' was when necessary (e.g. in looking at the impact of face coverings, where there was no credible estimate for effectiveness), and tried to give an overall qualitative summary of findings, while being transparent about what underlay those estimates.
Q23:
As described previously I tried to be as transparent as possible. For example I used curve fitting to case/death data to estimate R0 in this setting. I would show both fits (data+curves) along with a list of assumptions underlying the analysis.
I never interacted directly with ministers. My role was to provide scientific advice to other scientists who would synthesise my work with other taskforce workstreams. As such it was a discussion between scientific peers, and this influenced what I presented.

Q17#1_1_1: Basic epi parameters, clinical presentation, import potential to Europe, potential scale, first crisis response e.g. shipping ventilators from one EU Member State to another, sharing doctors, potential impact of border closures
Q17#1_2_1: How bad will it be? What is the objective e.g. minimising death, minimising economic impact, hospital overload. Potential interventions. Border closures (always). Testing strategies, contact tracing
Q17#1_3_1: When will it peak, how high will the peak be, how long will the peak be. Vaccine impact potential, vaccine prioritisation. Social contact reduction measures, interventions by age. Border closures (always). How to compare data across EU/EEA Member States
Q17#1_4_1: What next? Adherence to interventions. Testing, contact tracing. Are we collecting the right data? Is there an agreed objective yet? Border closures (always). What is the potential impact of increasing vaccination coverage? Should we have booster doses? For whom?
Q17#1_5_1: What data should we collect? How can data streams by synthesised? Compared? How can we learn from past experience without assuming history will repeat itself? Thankfully no one's asking me about border closures anymore!
Q19: All sorts, see previous text. In COVID-19 the questions about vaccines came later but for other pathogens they will be pertinent from the very beginning
Q21: It really depended to whom I was speaking. We could talk for a couple of hours on this alone. In general, I stressed the importance of synthesising different evidence streams, tried to highlight the sensitivity to different factors (including advocating for additional data collection) and used illustration and narrative as much as possible. I am particularly interested in the cultural and linguistic context of risk and uncertainty and diversity was certainly in evidence in the EU/EEA.
